        </div>
        <div class="column col-color bg3">
            <h2>Between <u>borders and boundaries</u>...</h2>
            <p class='p-more'>
                Territorial borders exist to create a <u class='highlighter3'>physical or political line</u> that separates geographic areas (National Geographic | Encyclopedic Entry, 2011). 
                These boundaries exist to imply political implications, where these implications may either be of <u class='highlighter3'>peace or violence.</u>
                <br><br> 
	            Such an example is the <u class='highlighter3'>demilitarized zone</u> that draws the line between North Korea and South Korea. With both entities holding each other with hostility, 
                it is a prime example of the <u class='highlighter3'>violent implications</u> that were mentioned. Not all boundaries exist to denote violence, the enjoining countries that comprise 
                the <u class='highlighter3'>European Union</u> can freely move in-between borders <u class='highlighter3'>without the ensuing uproar</u> like North and South Korea.

            
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
    </section>
    <!-- BG7 -->
     <section>
    <div class="row splitRow filler " data-aos="fade-right" data-aos-duration='1500'>
        <div class="column bg1">
            <h2>Seeking <u>refuge</u>...</h2>
            <p class = 'p-more'>
                Habitat for Humanity describes <u class='highlighter1'>refugees</u> as people who <u class='highlighter1'>flee from the dangers</u> of armed conflicts and persecution. <u class='highlighter1'>Asylum seekers</u> are then defined as someone who <u class='highlighter1'>claims to be a refugee but whose claim is unverified</u>. Lastly, <u class='highlighter1'>migrants</u> are defined as people who choose to move not out of safety, but <u class='highlighter1'>to improve their lives</u> (“Refugees, Asylum Seekers & Migrants: A Crucial Difference”, 2016).
                <br><br>
                The interchangeable meanings behind the classification of people who wish to flee their country <u class='highlighter1'>can cause confusion to the locals of the community</u>. The <u class='highlighter1'>stigma against foreign entities</u> entering the community <u class='highlighter1'>further complicates</u> the politics happening behind the scenes. Authorities can <u class'highlighter1'>neither be too lax nor too stern</u> towards entry as <u class='highlighter1'>circumstances may differ</u> from one entrant to another.

            </p>
        </div>
        <div class="column content-7">
        </div>
    </div>
    </section>
    <!-- BG8 -->
    <section>
    <div class="row splitRow filler  " data-aos="fade-left" data-aos-duration='1500'>
        <div class="column content-8">
        </div>
        <div class="column col-color bg2">
            <h2>Finding <u>community and acceptance</u>...</h2>
            <p class='p-more'>
                The policies surrounding migrants, refugees, and asylum seekers are <u class='highlighter2'>complex, at best</u>. Allowing these people the right to be a 
                part of the community is the <u class='highlighter2'>first step towards acceptance</u>, but the next is allowing these people to experience the same highs 
                that the community enjoys.
                <br><br>
                Sympathizing with struggles, the creation
                of safe spaces, and more, are ways to welcome these people into our community (“Exploring the Impact of Social Acceptance on Refugee Integration into Host Communities: Policy Research“, 2017). 
                <u class='highlighter2'>Blurring the political aspect of borders will leave 
                only leave the physical aspect of boundarie</u>s, yet ensuring the comfort of both locals and foreign entrants <u class='highlighter2'>definitely adds another
                layer to the complexity of territories, boundaries, and rights.</u>
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
